+summary.push('Adverse or lower-response main effects were also present. feature_027 level 2 had lower response than levels 0/1 (' + `${fmtPct(feature027Level2.effect)}, p=${rawP(feature027Level2.p)}), and the one-level feature_027 trend was ${fmtPct(feature027Slope.effect)} (p=${rawP(feature027Slope.p)}. ` + `High feature_004 and high feature_031 were associated with lower response (${fmtPct(high004Q.effect)} and ${fmtPct(high031Q.effect)}, respectively). ` + `feature_001 and feature_032 also had negative univariate risk differences (${fmtPct(bin.feature_001.effect)} and ${fmtPct(bin.feature_032.effect)}).`);
+summary.push('');
+summary.push('Interaction analyses showed that the favorable binary features were strongly non-additive. The feature_025 x feature_015 additive interaction was ' + `${fmtPct(int025015.effect)} (p=${rawP(int025015.p)}), feature_025 x feature_023 was ${fmtPct(int025023.effect)} (p=${rawP(int025023.p)}), and feature_015 x feature_023 was ${fmtPct(int015023.effect)} (p=${rawP(int015023.p)}). ` + `Patients positive for all three features had response ${fmtPct(tripleAssoc.p1)} versus ${fmtPct(tripleAssoc.p0)} in all others (risk difference ${fmtPct(tripleAssoc.effect)}, p=${rawP(tripleAssoc.p)}). The formal three-way additive contrast was ${fmtPct(triple.effect)} (p=${rawP(triple.p)}), so the triple-positive subgroup exceeded the lower-order additive pattern as well.`);
+summary.push('');
+summary.push('Resistance-like heterogeneity was observed for feature_001 and feature_032. feature_001 attenuated the feature_025 association (feature_025 x feature_001 interaction ' + `${fmtPct(int025001.effect)}, p=${rawP(int025001.p)}), and feature_032 attenuated the feature_025 association (${fmtPct(int025032.effect)}, p=${rawP(int025032.p)}). ` + `Similar attenuation appeared for feature_015 x feature_001 (${fmtPct(int015001.effect)}) and feature_023 x feature_032 (${fmtPct(int023032.effect)}).`);
+summary.push('');
+summary.push('A selected robust-SE linear probability model retained the three favorable pairwise interactions after adjustment: feature_025_x_feature_015 ' + `${fmtPct(adj.feature_025_x_feature_015.coef)} (p=${rawP(adj.feature_025_x_feature_015.p)}), feature_025_x_feature_023 ${fmtPct(adj.feature_025_x_feature_023.coef)} (p=${rawP(adj.feature_025_x_feature_023.p)}), and feature_015_x_feature_023 ${fmtPct(adj.feature_015_x_feature_023.coef)} (p=${rawP(adj.feature_015_x_feature_023.p)}). ` + `In that interaction-adjusted model, feature_001 (${fmtPct(adj.feature_001.coef)}, p=${rawP(adj.feature_001.p)}) and feature_032 (${fmtPct(adj.feature_032.coef)}, p=${rawP(adj.feature_032.p)}) did not retain independent adverse main effects, while feature_027 and feature_004 remained negative.`);
+summary.push('');
+summary.push('Exploratory analyses separated weaker signals from the dominant pattern. feature_059 high quartile had a small positive association and feature_053 high quartile had a small negative association. In contrast, feature_005 and feature_074 univariate hypotheses were not significant at p<0.05, and the proposed feature_005 x feature_013 interaction was also not significant. Median-split feature_004 and feature_027 level 2 did not materially modify the feature_025 association.');
+summary.push('');
+summary.push('The exhaustive binary-pair screen supported the same structure: the most significant adequate-cell interactions were dominated by feature_025, feature_015, feature_023, feature_001, and feature_032. Overall, objective response in this AML cohort appears driven by a strong treatment/biomarker-like interaction pattern among the three favorable opaque features, with adverse feature_027/feature_004 effects and attenuation by feature_001 and feature_032. Because the dataset is anonymized and observational, these findings are exploratory associations rather than causal clinical conclusions.');
+summary.push('');
